Gemini said
In the architecture we are moving toward, the Playwright script is not "always on" in the way you might think. Instead, the Browser is always on, and your script is triggered on-demand.

Think of it like a restaurant:

The Browser (Browserless in ACA): This is the Chef. He is always in the kitchen (always running) waiting for an order.

The Playwright Script: This is the Order. When a user clicks "Sync," your backend sends this "order" to the Chef. The script runs, tells the Chef what to do, and as soon as the "meal" (the session data) is served, the script finishes and disappears.

1. Is the script "Always On"?
   No. Your Playwright script is a short-lived execution.

It starts when the user clicks "Sync."

It connects to the "Warm" browser in milliseconds.

It does its job (navigates, checks login, scrapes).

It terminates as soon as it's done.

2. Is the Browser "Always On"?
   Yes. This is the "Warm" part.

The Browserless container in Azure Container Apps (ACA) stays running 24/7 (or scales up/down as needed).

Because Chrome is already "booted up" inside that container, there is zero delay when your script says connectOverCDP.

Comparison of "Always On" vs. "On Demand"
Component Status Why?
Azure Container App (ACA) Always On To eliminate the 60-second "Cold Start" boot time.
Browserless Service Always On To keep the browser engine ready to accept connections.
Your Playwright Script On Demand To save resources; it only runs when a user actually needs a sync.
Azure File Share Always Mounted So the Browser can immediately access the user's saved cookies/session.
How it looks in your Code
You'll stop using chromium.launch() (which starts a new browser) and start using chromium.connectOverCDP() (which talks to the one already running).

JavaScript
// This script runs "on-demand" when the Sync button is clicked
async function runSyncTask(userId) {
// 1. Connects INSTANTLY to the "Always On" browser
const browser = await chromium.connectOverCDP(`wss://your-domain.com?id=${userId}`);

// 2. The script executes its logic
const page = await browser.newPage();
await page.goto("https://facebook.com/marketplace");

// 3. The script FINISHES and exits here.
// The browser stays alive for the next script that comes along.
await browser.close();
}
Why this is a win:
Script speed: The "startup" part of your script goes from 60 seconds to 0.5 seconds.

Memory: You don't have 100 copies of Chrome running; you have one efficient Browserless service handling multiple users.

Simplicity: Your script doesn't need to manage "booting" the OS or "setting up" noVNC; it just focuses on the Facebook logic.

