Exactly. You are moving from a "Script that is the whole container" to an "API that controls a browser."

In this new architecture, your Playwright script lives inside a standard Express.js API. This API is the "Always On" part that stays running in your Azure Container App.

The New Architecture
Instead of Azure starting a container to run a script, the container is already running your Express app. When a request hits your /sync endpoint, Express simply executes your Playwright function.

Here is what the code looks like now:
JavaScript
import express from "express";
import { chromium } from "playwright";

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

// This is the "Service URL" for your always-running Browserless container
const BROWSER_WS_ENDPOINT = `wss://your-browserless-service.com?token=YOUR_TOKEN`;

// --- YOUR PLAYWRIGHT LOGIC (The "Worker") ---
async function performSync(userId) {
// 1. Connect to the WARM browser instantly
// We point it to the Azure File Share mount for this specific user
const browser = await chromium.connectOverCDP(
`${BROWSER_WS_ENDPOINT}&--user-data-dir=/data/browser-sessions/${userId}`
);

try {
const context = browser.contexts()[0]; // Get the context created by user-data-dir
const page = await context.newPage();

    console.log(`[${userId}] Checking login...`);
    await page.goto("https://www.facebook.com/login");

    // ... Insert your isLoggedIn check and Marketplace logic here ...
    // If you need a human, you return the Debugger URL:
    // `https://your-browserless-service.com/debugger?id=${userId}`

    return { success: true };

} finally {
// 2. CRITICAL: We close the connection so we don't leak memory,
// but the Browserless "Chef" stays alive for the next order.
await browser.close();
}
}

// --- THE API ENDPOINT ---
app.post("/sync", async (req, res) => {
const { userId } = req.body;

try {
// We trigger the script logic on-demand
const result = await performSync(userId);
res.json(result);
} catch (err) {
res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
}
});

app.listen(8080, () => console.log("Sync API is warm and listening..."));
Why this is the "final form" of your infra:
The API is Always On: Your backend calls POST /sync. There is zero Azure startup delay.

The Browser is Always On: The Playwright code connects to the browser in under 500ms.

The Context is Persisted: Because you pass the --user-data-dir, the browser automatically picks up the cookies from your Azure File Share mount instantly.

No Copying Logic: You no longer need to write code to move folders around. The browser reads directly from the mount.

Where is the user's VNC/Debugger URL?
